#import "../../lib.typ": chapter

#chapter(5, "Introduction")[
  After a while of sightseeing, Mona headed towards her class for the first
  period.

  All main classrooms resided in the Misuzu main building, with every grade
  occupied exactly one floor, so it was very straightforward for newcomers to
  find their classrooms.

  For example, excluding the first floor that was reserved for special purposes,
  the second floor exclusively consisted of third-year classrooms. Then, on the
  third floor resided those for the first-year students, and finally the
  second-years on the fourth floor.

  Now, it might seem unintuitive at first that the order was third-years,
  first-years and then second-years, but the school actually had its reasons.

  Third-years were the ones that had to work the hardest in the school, with
  upcoming university exams and whatnot. So, the school subtly reduced their
  burden by lessening the amount of walking they needed to take every day. For
  the first-years and the second-years, it made sense to let the newcomers walk
  less, as a welcoming tribute to their efforts on the entrance exam. The
  second-years, who had to walk the most, still found it quite convenient, as
  the clubrooms, where they hanged out a lot, were right there on the next
  floor.

  After finding out where she would spend most of the school year at, Mona
  entered her classroom for the first time.

  She took a quick look at the situation. There were some groups already
  forming, which probably consists of people that knew each other since middle
  school, but most of the class was sitting on their seats doing their own
  things.

  Much like most of the class, Mona was also someone without any acquaintances,
  not to mention that she was not particularly close to anyone in middle school.
  However, she was not anti-social like these edgy protagonists in anime, and
  she could keep up with other people’s conversations. But as she spent more and
  more time on her personal worship of idols, she started to lose touch with her
  peers.

  On her middle school graduation day, she just went there, take her
  certifications and documents, shoot some group photos with the rest of the
  class and some groups that somehow wanted her to be in their photos, then went
  home. End of story. And it’s not like she was the only one like that. Half of
  her class also had a similar experience on that day. Only the social
  butterflies stayed for longer and made it look like that this day was actually
  much longer than it should have been.

  Once she found a suitable seat to sit at, Mona took out her phone and looked
  at the idol news feed on her social media, continuing at where she left off.
  There were still five minutes until class start, just enough time for some
  more swiping. Thanks to her extensive block list of toxic accounts, her news
  feed only consists of positive news and, occasionally, massive scandals that
  were too significant to ignore. The positivity she saw on her phone was able
  to give her the necessary amount of energy for the day.

  After a while scrolling through her daily dose of idol pet and beverage
  pictures, Mona heard the bell rang and saw her new teacher entering the
  classroom. It was a young man, who looked like a fresh graduate from some
  prestigious university. Make sense, it was Misuzu after all. After a brief
  introduction about himself, he was able to capture everyone’s attention.

  "How about we do a self-introduction so that everyone in the class can get to
  know each other better?"

  Mona, was her thoughts still on the cloud with the recent idol news, were
  caught off-guard. Why is self-introduction still a thing in high school, she
  thought, isn’t it just a thing in shoujo manga? Or maybe he’s into this kind
  of stuff?

  As Mona hurriedly tried to make a script of what to say, her classmates, one
  by one, stood up and introduced themselves. Some girls were able to neatly
  introduce themselves, while some, seemingly more shy and introverted, were
  cheered on by their friends, ended up with some semi-acceptable lines.

  And when it was her turn, she clumsily stood up. The class went silent.

  Unlike those shy girls before her, Mona had no friends to cheer her on.

  "I’m Narumi Mona. My hobbies are watching TV and listening to music. I hope in
  the next three years, we can be good friends with each other."

  "How generic."

  "Everyone likes watching TV and listening to music, do you have anything
  better to say about yourself."

  Mona’s own voices of self-criticism in her heads pulled her right back to her
  seat straight away.

  It was a total failure. Her last-minute efforts could only make such a bland
  and mediocre self-introduction.

  Mona was a straightforward and honest girl. In a world where bubbly worlds
  with no meanings got thrown all over the place, genuine words coming from
  one’s heart could earn the respect of people around them.

  Or it was what Mona thought. In reality, people without the ability to lie can
  always have the risk of offending people around them. Hence, such people had
  two choices. Either to deal with the troubles that their world brought upon,
  or to shut their mouths and keep silent.

  As the world getting bigger and bigger, a human life became less and less
  significant, and it had become increasingly harder for one to cope with the
  consequences of their words.

  Hence, most honest people decided to close their mouths.

  By omitting important bits of their true thoughts, honest people had become
  dishonest.

  Mona was no exception. Though she loved idols, she could not blurt out her
  passionate enthusiasm to her middle school classmates. And just now, she did
  not have any mention of idols in her self-introduction, even though she did
  mention topics like TV and music, which somewhat have an overlap with show
  business.

  "Narumi Mona? Is she related with…"

  "She did mention that she had a younger sister, maybe she is actually…"

  Much to Mona’s surprise, she heard subtle chattering noises all around the
  class. The noises were coming from different groups within her class, but it
  was not loud enough for her to make sense of.

  Though, what Mona cared about more is her embarrassing speech before her
  entire new class. This moment would probably go down as one of her worst event
  ever in her high-school life, haunting her for years to come.
]
